explanation:
For determining whether any operations in OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete constitute dead code the analyzer must know the semantics and actual callsite usage that make those operations observable or not:

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish: Required to know what side-effects occur when &final_id is passed (e.g. does it update global object tables, restore IDs, release resources). If this call performs observable state changes, the assignments to final_id are not dead.

- OS_NotifyEvent: Required to know whether invoking this function produces observable behavior (callbacks, logging, IPC). If it has side-effects visible outside the module, the call is not dead.

- OS_EVENT_RESOURCE_DELETED: The specific event constant passed to OS_NotifyEvent; needed to interpret the effect of the notification and whether it is handled by the system/app (i.e. observable).

- OS_OBJECT_ID_UNDEFINED: The concrete value assigned to final_id when operation_status == OS_SUCCESS; needed to know whether assigning this value is meaningful to subsequent calls (e.g. used by OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish).

- OS_SUCCESS: The constant used in the conditional; needed to understand which branch(es) can execute and whether one branch is impossible at all call sites.

- OS_object_token_t (definition including obj_id): The structure definition and semantics of token->obj_id are required to determine what restoring token->obj_id into final_id does (observable change or no-op).

- osal_id_t (typedef/definition): To understand representation/aliasing of final_id and whether assignments/updates could have side-effects (alignment, special values, etc.).

- All callers of OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete (OS_BinSemDelete, OS_CondVarDelete, OS_CountSemDelete, OS_DirectoryClose, OS_close, OS_rmfs, OS_ModuleUnload, OS_MutSemDelete, OS_QueueDelete, OS_TaskDelete, OS_TaskExit, OS_TimeBaseDelete, OS_TimerDelete): To decide if a particular branch is ever exercised in practice (dead code per MISRA is an operation that can be executed but whose removal would not change behavior). If callers always pass operation_status values that force one branch, the other branch may be effectively dead; analyzing the callers shows what operation_status values are actually passed.

Providing these symbols (implementations/specs and callers) allows the next agent to determine whether the assignments, the call to OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish, and the conditional OS_NotifyEvent call are observable and thus not dead, or removable without affecting program behaviour.
